"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137633","Wales Office","false","2019-07-11","<p>Wylfa Newydd remains a suitable site for nuclear new build in the future. The site is still owned by Hitachi, and the UK Government remains in discussions with them regarding its future.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to creating a broad-based resilient economy through our modern Industrial Strategy and will continue to work with the Welsh Government and local partners to ensure that North Wales prospers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains committed to the nuclear sector, giving the go ahead to the first new nuclear power station in a generation at Hinkley Point C and investing £200m through our landmark Nuclear Sector Deal, which was signed in North Wales.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2019-07-11T10:45:32.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137633/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137633/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-07-08","Wylfa Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent progress the Government has made on the future of the proposed Wylfa Newydd power plant.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","274449"
