"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137160","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-10","<p>NHS England has committed to increase the national grant funding from £12 million to £25 million a year by 2023/24. The planned grant allocations by financial year are as follows: 2020/21 £15 million; 2021/22 £17 million; 2022/23 £21 million; 2023/24 £25 million.</p><p>NHS England is undertaking a review of the current grant allocation formula which is due to complete by the end of this year. Following agreement with the sector, it is planned to notify the 2020/21 grant allocations prior to the start of 2020/21 financial year in line with National Health Service operational planning processes.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","273783 ; 273784 ; 273785","2019-07-10T16:18:48.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137160/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137160/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-05","Hospices: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that children’s hospices receive notice of their individual 2020-21 NHS England children’s hospice grant allocation in time to inform their budget planning for that year.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","273786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137161","Treasury","false","2019-07-10","<p>I refer the Right Honourable Member to the response given on 8th July 2019 to Parliamentary Question 272873.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-07-10T07:28:46.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137161/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137161/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-07-05","Sugar: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much revenue his Department received though collection of the sugar tax in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","273729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137162","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-15","<p>The National Diet and Nutrition Survey is used to monitor consumption trends in the United Kingdom population. Data covering the period after publication of the Childhood Obesity Plan will become available in 2020.</p><p>As part of the Childhood Obesity Plan, Public Health England (PHE) oversees a sugar reduction programme. In May 2018, PHE published a report assessing progress in the first year of the programme. This showed sugar in retailer own brand and manufacturer branded products reduced by 2% overall, with larger reductions in some individual product categories. Sugar in drinks covered by the Soft Drinks Industry Levy reduced by 11%. Data also showed that consumers are buying more drinks that have sugar levels below five grams per 100 millilitres. The report is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/709008/Sugar_reduction_progress_report.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/709008/Sugar_reduction_progress_report.pdf</a></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-07-15T16:26:56.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137162/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137162/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-05","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care,  with reference to the Childhood Obesity Plan: a plan for action, chapter 2, published on 25 June 2018, what progress he has made on reducing children's consumption of sugary drinks and food.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","273730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137163","Department for Education","false","2019-07-10","<p>Schools are responsible for their day-to-day running, including their school meals service. I refer the right hon. Member for Birkenhead to the answer I gave on 5 July 2019 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2019-06-27/270292/" target="_blank">270292</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-10T12:33:47.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137163/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137163/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-05","Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will make it his policy to require schools to offer pupils breakfast on the morning of their exams.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","273743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137164","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-10","<p>As part of the NHS Long Term Plan, we are establishing specialist Alcohol Care Teams (ACTs) in hospitals with the highest rates of alcohol harm. It is estimated that this will prevent 50,000 admissions over five years.</p><p>All clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have been allocated a Health Inequalities Funding Supplement contribution to their indicative baselines. NHS England and NHS Improvement, through the Long Term Plan, have highlighted the evidence base for ACTs and indicated that where required, commissioners should utilise monies from this funding supplement to close health inequality gaps associated with alcohol dependence.</p><p>Additionally, for those areas with the highest levels of demand, additional targeted monies will be invested directly to ensure the provision of optimal ACTs starting from 2020/21.</p><p>Local authorities will also receive over £3 billion in 2019/20 to be used exclusively on public health including alcohol treatment services.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","273735","2019-07-10T16:19:02.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137164/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137164/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-05","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Government is taking to fund at least one alcohol care team or specialist in every hospital.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","273736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137165","Department for Education","false","2019-07-10","<p>Information on when schools finish their school day is not held centrally.</p><p>It is unacceptable for schools to shorten their working week when it is not a direct action to support and enhance their pupils’ education. According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies, funding for the average primary school class is £132,000, and funding for that same class of children in secondary school would be £171,000. These amounts are to cover a full five-day week in term time.</p><p>All schools have the autonomy to decide the structure and duration of their school day, which includes the flexibility to decide when their school day should start and finish. The Department trusts that headteachers will do this in a sensible manner.</p><p>All maintained schools are required to educate pupils for at least 380 sessions each school year. They cannot reduce the length of the school week if this would take the total number of sessions below that.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-07-10T14:04:54.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137165/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137165/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-05","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many hours of schooling were lost due to schools reducing the length of the school day as a result of insufficient funding in the 2017-18 academic year.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","273737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137166","Department for Education","false","2019-07-10","<p>The Department takes the safety of pupils, staff and visitors to schools very seriously.</p><p>In 2016, the Department ran a voluntary survey to understand the proportion of school buildings that contain asbestos. 25% of schools responded and the findings showed that 83.1% had asbestos present.</p><p>In March 2018, the Department launched the Asbestos Management Assurance Process to develop a more comprehensive understanding of asbestos management in the school estate to strengthen our published guidance and support. 88.4% of schools responded to the latest survey and the Department intends to publish the report on the findings before summer recess.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-07-10T12:42:16.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137166/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137166/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-05","Schools: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the proportion of school buildings that contain asbestos; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","273787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137167","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-10","<p>Regulation 4 of the Control of Asbestos Regulation 2012 requires duty holders (normally the owner or person responsible for maintenance of the building) in all public sector buildings to identify and record the presence and condition of asbestos-containing materials. In practice, this will require a survey of the building and, if necessary, the testing of any material suspected of containing asbestos.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-10T12:18:47.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137167/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137167/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-05","Buildings: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what her Department's policy is on mandatory asbestos testing in public sector buildings.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","273788"
